name: La Vieille aux Loques
description: The composition points to the beginning of Whistler’s preoccupation throughout his career with façades and doorways and, more specifically, with the motif of a female figure silhouetted in a doorway against a darkened interior. It is likely that this work was etched in Paris and was published in 'Twelve Etchings from Nature' (the 'French Set') in 1858. A translation of the title is 'Old Rag Woman' or 'Old Rag Seller.'

name: The Great Wave off the Coast of Kanagawa
description: This iconic composition comes from the golden age of Japanese woodblock printmaking. Hokusai manages, through the clever and dramatic manipulation of space, to dwarf Japan's snow-capped Mt. Fuji with the enormous wave, which is about to crash down in the foreground.

details.title: Title:
details.description: The Great Wave off the Coast of Kanagawa

name: Appeal to the Great Spirit
description: Dallin lived among the Utes while Utah was being settled by the Mormons and the Pacific Railroad was being completed. After extended periods of conflict, the Utes (Paiutes and Shoshone) were forced onto reservations. In this bronze, Dallin looked back to that period and reconstructed a sympathetic tribute to the memory of the ignoble treatment of a proud people. The composition won a medal in 1909 at the Paris Salon.

name: A Study in White
description: This alluring portrait of a young woman in a white dress seated on a hill, presumably under a tree, demonstrates the general principles of American Impressionism around the turn of the century. The painting captures the fleeting impression of sharp contrast of light and the deep, rich colors of a summer day, with bold, visible brushstrokes in a lightened color palette. One gets the sense that the painting captures a contemplative moment of rest painted outdoors.

name: Amber, Jade, and Amethyst
description: Titled for the magnificent jewel-like colors reflected in the crashing surf, this large seascape depicts the dramatic moment when the clouds separate and allow the sun’s golden light to shine through. The water reflects the light and rushes toward the rocky coastline in dramatic fashion. The artist noted, “I have always believed in establishing the sky tone, in general, as soon as possible. In sea painting, the rest depends upon it because of the element of reflection.”

name: End of the Trail
description: When displayed at the 1915 Panama - Pacific Exposition in San Francisco, End of the Trail was instantly recognized as one of the defining images to come out of America's Western heritage. In despair and submission, the rider has dropped his lance, bent his back and bowed his head. His horse, too, reflects the no longer proud posture of his master's glorious tradition. By 1893, when the composition was created, the Sioux had been forced into Dakota country and all but vanished as a nation.

name: Chance Meeting
description: Australian-born Lewis specialized in New York street scenes and became one of the leading printmakers in America in the years leading up to WWII. This shadowy street scene shows an encounter between a young man and a woman outside a newsstand. Light from the shop shines out into the sidewalk, illuminating the young man, whose hands are in his pockets. A prominent 7-Up sign looms above them, and in the window, a magazine titled “True Love” can be seen. In the background, a second pair of figures engages in a nocturnal flirtation.

name: Man Reading (Nicola d’Inverno)
description: Born to expatriate American parents in Florence, Sargent began his formal training in Rome in the late 1860s. His studies took him to Florence in the early 1870s and to Paris by the mid-1870s. By the turn of the century, he was the leading portrait artist on the Continent and in great demand among the elite. The sitter of this rather loosely painted sketch of a man reading is most likely Nicola d’Inverno, the artist’s manservant who was in his service from the 1890s through 1917. The painting may have been painted at the inn at Purtud in the Italian Alps, where Sargent and his friends spent several summers between 1904 and 1908.

name: Pietà
description: One of the most moving of Annibale’s etchings, the Pietà emphasizes the sorrow of the Virgin. The artist treated the subject in paintings, drawings, and prints. This edition was published by Nicolas van Aelst, the Belgian engraver and publisher, who likely printed a later state of Annibale’s plate in the 16-teens.

name: Trout Fishing in the Catskills
description: Whittredge was born in Ohio and apprenticed at the age of seventeen as a sign painter in Cincinnati and worked for a time as a photographer in Indianapolis. The artist turned to landscape painting by the mid-1840s, adopting the Hudson River School style of Thomas Doughty and Thomas Cole. In this forest interior, a lone fisherman is positioned near a large rock formation at the center of the composition. The cascading waterfall is flanked by an area of darkness on the left and sunlit pines on the right.

name: The Balloon (Le Ballon)
description: This monumental canvas records a moment of rest and wonder. Six peasants take pause from their labor in the fields to observe the appearance of a large hot air balloon high in the sky. The positions of the nearly life-size figures, with their backs to the observer, are meant to draw the viewer into the composition in a participatory role. The viewer is prompted to look up into the sky and behold the wonder of the balloon with the group of peasant farmers. Hot air balloons had been in use in Europe since the 1780s but even one hundred years later, in the 1880s, balloons were a rare sight, inspiring awe, especially in the French countryside.

name: Lotus Pool, El Encanto, Santa Barbara
description: By the early 1920s, there were several exquisitely landscaped resort hotels that attracted the attention of Cooper, who was born in Philadelphia and who had studied at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts. El Encanto (The Enchanted) became a favorite location for the artist. He made several paintings of the pond and pergola. This painting is a foreshortened view of the pond looking out toward the pergola and eucalyptus trees in the distance. The lush landscape is bathed in sunlight exhibiting his mastery of the plein air technique.

details.title: Title:
details.description: Lotus Pool, El Encanto, Santa Barbara

name: Isis with Horus
description: Isis is the wife of Osiris and mother of Horus and in groupings like this one, is always seen as a protector and life-giver. She appears seated on a throne, nursing her son, and wears the vulture headdress with horned crown, that was adopted from Hathor in the later period.

name: Annie Seated
description: The sitter in this work is the artist's niece, Annie Haden, who was about nine or ten years old when Whistler recorded her. Whistler spent Christmas in London with Annie's parents Francis Seymour Haden and Deborah Delano Haden—Whistler’s half-sister. This is one of Whistler's early figure studies of children; others include 'Annie', 'Little Arthur', and 'Seymour Standing' all from 1857-8.

name: Japanese Peasant Girl
description: Like Louis Comfort Tiffany, John La Farge was a painter, stained glass artist, muralist, and interior designer based in New York. This painting was completed in 1886, the year the artist visited Japan with his friend, historian Henry Adams. The loosely handled brush work combines a sense of the exotic and a somber tone. The artist published a book in 1897 titled, An Artist’s Letters from Japan, one of eight books and numerous essays LaFarge wrote over the course of his career.
